<font color="#FF0000">RESPONSE TO VARANELLI</font><br>
<tt>Sat Feb  8  0:53:27 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Arthur- As for Vietnam &amp; French colonialism: Ho Chi Minh asked our govt. 7 times during and after his country's occupation by the Japanese during WWII if we would assist the Vietnamese in gaining their independence.  He dared to think that our country, which had struggled against a European power many years before to gain its independence, would understand and &quot;talk&quot; to the French.  Alas, after the Japanese left we assisted the French in re-establishing their colonial empire.  The rest, as they say, is history.  But how could history have been different if we had told the French that they should &quot;let go&quot; of Vietnam as we had finally let go of the Philippines?*******Back to protests, the &quot;root&quot; of this part of P.O.V.'s Dialog:  I don't think very many protestors spit on, cursed, hated, etc., returning vets.  Surely, the ones that did were covered by the media. But there must have been 1,000 or more who protested simply by marching, sitting in, or writing letters for every one of those jerks who carried NV flags, spat, etc.  I realize if a vet was spat on it left a deep emotional scar.  But because one protester spat on him doesn't mean all protesters were so callous, thoughtless and, dare I say, idiotic.  As for the Protest Movement ending the war, I think that's ridiculous.  In 1964 80% of the Amer. people supported the war; by 1970 (?) 80% opposed the war.  I think you are right about the natural progression of things, but I think that part of that progression was people questioning what the hell our leaders were doing.  Not many asked in 1964.  Millions (tens of millions) were asking by 1970.*****PBS just re-broadcast &quot;The Gulf War,&quot; and it was v-e-r-y interesting once again listening to all the different reasons Pres. Bush gave, at different times, in an attempt to explain to the American people why we were going over there and (possibly) risking tens of thousands of Amer. lives- &quot;Hussein is a dictator...&quot; &quot;H has nuclear weapons...&quot; &quot;H has biological and chemical weapons of mass destruction...&quot; &quot;We must preserve democracy....&quot; &quot;Blah, blah, blah....&quot;  &quot;Etc.&quot; &quot;Etc.&quot; All bullshit that very few of us fell for. Then he f-i-n-a-l-l-y told us it was because SH now had 20% of the world's oil and if he invaded Saudi Arabia he'd have 40% and we couldn't let him do that.  I think the lesson the public learned from Vietnam made it impossible for Bush to bullshit us.  [Of course, Reagan bullshitted us with Grenada, but that's another story.] Thanks to Vietnam our leaders have to be v-e-r-y careful about where they are sending our men and women, and why.  I DO NOT think this is a bad thing.  
<p><code>--   (Nurse Ratchet) </code><p>


